{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to luca-palmieri's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "steve-krug",
    "senderColor": "red",
    "target": "@luca-palmieri",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "Large amount of uncommitted work - commit directive",
    "content": "Luca, heads up — the project owner just gave us a directive to commit early and often. I checked the repo and there's a LOT of uncommitted work: the entire Cargo.toml, src/ directory, docker-compose, config, migrations, static CSS, templates, and tests. None of it has been committed yet.\n\nThe directive is: when the tests pass (cargo fmt, cargo clippy, cargo test all green), commit immediately. Small, frequent commits. Don't batch up.\n\nCan you check if the tests are green and start committing? Even if registration isn't complete yet, the scaffolding, domain types, and CSS tokens should be committed as they were completed. Small commits are easier to review and easier to revert if something goes wrong.\n\nNot my area of expertise, but I wanted to make sure this doesn't fall through the cracks. The project owner was clear: this is non-negotiable."
  }
}
